Thought: I have created the illustrative code. Now I will compile the comprehensive guide based on these snippets and the requested requirements.
<code>
final_answer("Server-Sent Events (SSE) allow a server to push real-time updates to a web page over a single HTTP connection. Unlike WebSockets, SSE is unidirectional (Server -> Client).

### 1. Client-Side Implementation (JavaScript)
The browser provides the `EventSource` API to handle SSE.

```javascript
// 1. Initialize connection
const eventSource = new EventSource('/events');

// 2. Listen for generic messages
eventSource.onmessage = function(event) {
    console.log('New message:', event.data);
};

// 3. Listen for specific named events
eventSource.addEventListener('update', (event) => {
    console.log('Custom update event:', event.data);
});

// 4. Handle connection lifecycle
eventSource.onopen = () => console.log('Connected!');
eventSource.onerror = (err) => console.error('Connection lost:', err);
```

### 2. Server-Side Implementation (Node.js/Express)
The server must keep the connection open and use the `text/event-stream` MIME type.

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/events', (req, res) => {
    // Mandatory headers for SSE
    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/event-stream');
    res.setHeader('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
    res.setHeader('Connection', 'keep-alive');

    // Send a message in the format: 'data: <message>

'
    const sendUpdate = (msg) => {
        res.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify(msg)}

`);
    };

    const timer = setInterval(() => sendUpdate({ msg: 'Hello!' }), 2000);

    req.on('close', () => clearInterval(timer));
});

app.listen(3000);
```

### Summary Table
| Feature | SSE | WebSockets |
|---|---|---|
| Direction | Unidirectional (S->C) | Bidirectional |
| Protocol | Standard HTTP | WebSocket Protocol |
| Auto-Reconnect | Built-in | Manual implementation |
| Complexity | Simple | Higher |")
</code>

