Thought: I have demonstrated the implementation. I can now provide the final answer explaining the pattern.
<code>
final_answer("Yes, while creating separate router files is the conventional way to keep a project maintainable, you can avoid manual repetition by dynamically loading your routes. 

A common pattern is to create a 'controllers' directory where each file defines a function to register its respective route. You can then use `fs.readdirSync` to loop through the directory and execute the registration function for every file found.

Example implementation:

1. Main App (app.js):
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
fs.readdirSync('./controllers').forEach((file) => {
  if (file.substr(-3) === '.js') {
    const route = require('./controllers/' + file);
    route.controller(app);
  }
});
```

2. Controller File (controllers/products.js):
```javascript
module.exports.controller = (app) => {
  app.use('/products', require('../routes/products'));
};
```

This approach is DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and ensures that any new route file added to the controllers folder is automatically registered without needing to modify the main entry point.")
</code>

