Thought: The code works. I can now explain that while you can technically redirect calls, you cannot avoid writing the wrapper methods in C# (as C# doesn't have native 'interface delegation' like Kotlin). I must also warn about the mistake of calling GetEnumerator() inside the properties.
<code>
final_answer("Yes, it is possible to delegate the implementation of the IEnumerator interface directly to _myList, although C# requires you to explicitly write the wrapper methods (delegation) as it doesn't support automatic interface delegation.

One critical warning: do NOT call `_myList.GetEnumerator().Current` directly inside the properties. Doing so creates a new enumerator object on every call, meaning MoveNext() and Current will not track the position correctly.

The correct approach is to store a reference to the enumerator returned by the list:

```csharp
public class MyEnum : IEnumerator<SomeObject>
{
    private List<SomeObject> _myList;
    private IEnumerator<SomeObject> _enumerator;

    public MyEnum(List<SomeObject> myList)
    {
        _myList = myList;
        _enumerator = _myList.GetEnumerator();
    }

    public SomeObject Current => _enumerator.Current;
    object IEnumerator.Current => _enumerator.Current;
    public bool MoveNext() => _enumerator.MoveNext();
    public void Reset() => _enumerator.Reset();
    public void Dispose() => _enumerator.Dispose();
}
```")
</code>

