<code>
final_answer("To properly implement error handling in a RESTful API using Express.js and resolve '500 Internal Server Errors', you should implement handling at three levels:

1. Route-specific middleware: Use try-catch blocks in your route handlers and pass errors to the next middleware using `next(error)`.
2. App-level middleware: Define a special error-handling middleware function with four arguments `(err, req, res, next)`. Express recognizes this signature and will skip all other middleware to reach this one when an error is passed.
3. Process-level handlers: Use `process.on('uncaughtException')` to catch errors that escape the Express framework entirely, allowing for graceful shutdown or logging.

Example implementation (saved to express_error_handling.js):

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/example-route', (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    throw new Error('An error occurred');
  } catch (error) {
    next(error);
  }
});

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error('App-level error: ', err.stack);
  res.status(500).json({ message: 'An internal error occurred' });
});

process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error('Unhandled exception: ', err.stack);
  process.exit(1);
});

app.listen(3000);
```

Additionally, always examine your server logs and stack traces to identify the specific line of code triggering the 500 error.")
